#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:13
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION: This hint describes step-by-step how to install the necessary "
"tools for IPsec (secure IP connections) under LFS and creates a basic "
"configuration file for a simple transport-mode IPsec connection using AH and "
"ESP protocols between two computers."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:16
msgid ""
"PREREQUISITES: To use this hit you will need a LFS system ready with kernel "
"2.6.10 and OpenSSL installed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:18
msgid "HINT:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:20
msgid "Using IPsec under LFS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:22
msgid ""
"Before you start, make sure you have a running LFS and OpenSSL installed. If "
"you need to install OpenSSL refer to the BLFS book. These installation "
"instructions (especially configuring ipsec) are based on the official IPsec "
"Howto for Linux."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:28
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1. Reconfiguring the kernel\n"
"Get the latest linux kernel source archive from www.kernel.org and unpack it "
"in /usr/src\n"
"$> cd /usr/src &&\n"
"$> wget http://www.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v2.6/linux-2.6.11.7.tar.bz2 "
"&&\n"
"$> tar xfj linux-2.6.11.7.tar.bz2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:33
msgid ""
"Copy your current kernel configuration to /usr/src/linux-2.6.11.7 and "
"reconfigure existing features $> cd /usr/src/linux-2.6.11.7 && $> cp "
"/boot/config-2.6.11.2 .config && $> make oldconfig"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:36
msgid ""
"Now customize the kernel features for IPsec support. Make sure you have "
"selected the following features $> make menuconfig"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:45
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Networking support (NET) [Y/n/?] y\n"
"  *\n"
"  * Networking options\n"
"  *\n"
"  PF_KEY sockets (NET_KEY) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
"  IP: AH transformation (INET_AH) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
"  IP: ESP transformation (INET_ESP) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
"  IP: IPsec user configuration interface (XFRM_USER) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:53
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Cryptographic API (CRYPTO) [Y/n/?] y\n"
"  HMAC support (CRYPTO_HMAC) [Y/n/?] y\n"
"  Null algorithms (CRYPTO_NULL) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
"  MD5 digest algorithm (CRYPTO_MD5) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
"  SHA1 digest algorithm (CRYPTO_SHA1) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
"  DES and Triple DES EDE cipher algorithms (CRYPTO_DES) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
"  AES cipher algorithms (CRYPTO_AES) [Y/n/m/?] y\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:62
msgid ""
"Compile and install your configured kernel. Reboot after changing your grub "
"config to boot the new kernel.  $> make bzImage && $> make modules_install "
"&& $> cp .config /boot/config-2.6.11.7 && $> cp arch/i386/boot/bzImage "
"/boot/linux-2.6.11.7 && $> cp System.map /boot/System.map-2.6.11.7 && $> vi "
"/boot/grub/menu.lst && $> reboot"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:68
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"2. Install ipsec-tools\n"
"download the lastest ipsec-tools source tarball from "
"ipsec-tools.sourceforge.net and unpack it in /usr/src\n"
"$> cd /usr/src &&\n"
"$> wget "
"http://switch.dl.sourceforge.net/sourceforge/ipsec-tools/ipsec-tools-0.5.1.tar.bz2 "
"&&\n"
"$> tar xfj ipsec-tools-0.5.1.tar.bz2 \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:74
msgid ""
"Configure, make and install the ipsec-tools. The ipsec-tools require some "
"kernel headers installed. The LFS book installs them in /usr/include $> cd "
"/usr/src/ipsec-tools-0.5.1 && $> ./configure --prefix=/usr "
"--with-kernel-headers=/usr/include && $> make && $> make install"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:86
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"3. Configure ipsec-tools\n"
"You will need two different configrations, one for each host because IPsec "
"works unidirectional. The example below is using the IPsec ah and esp "
"protocol in transport mode. To be able to reconfigure ipsec quickly after "
"rebooting the rules will be stored in /etc/setkey.conf.\n"
"$> cat > /etc/setkey.conf << \"EOF\"\n"
"$> # Begin 192.168.2.31's setkey.conf\n"
"$> # Drop all rules\n"
"$> flush;\n"
"$> spdflush;\n"
"$> \n"
"$> # AH SAs\n"
"$> add 192.168.2.31 192.168.2.32 ah 0x200 -A hmac-md5 "
"0xc0291ff014dccdd03874d9e8e4cdf3e6;\n"
"$> add 192.168.2.32 192.168.2.31 ah 0x300 -A hmac-md5 "
"0x96358c90783bbfa3d7b196ceabe0536b;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:96
msgid ""
"$> # ESP SAs using 192 bit long keys (168 + 24 parity)  $> add 192.168.2.31 "
"192.168.2.32 esp 0x201 -E 3des-cbc "
"0x7aeaca3f87d060a12f4a4487d5a5c3355920fae69a96c831; $> add 192.168.2.32 "
"192.168.2.31 esp 0x301 -E 3des-cbc "
"0xf6ddb555acfd9d77b03ea3843f2653255afe8eb5573965df; $> $> # Security "
"policies $> spdadd 192.168.2.31 192.168.2.32 any -P out ipsec "
"esp/transport//require ah/transport//require; $> spdadd 192.168.2.32 "
"192.168.2.31 any -P in ipsec esp/transport//require ah/transport//require; "
"$> # End setkey.conf $> EOF"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:116
msgid ""
"$> cat > /etc/setkey.conf << \"EOF\" $> # Begin 192.168.2.32's setkey.conf "
"$> # Drop all rules $> flush; $> spdflush; $> $> # AH SAs $> add "
"192.168.2.31 192.168.2.32 ah 0x200 -A hmac-md5 "
"0xc0291ff014dccdd03874d9e8e4cdf3e6; $> add 192.168.2.32 192.168.2.31 ah "
"0x300 -A hmac-md5 0x96358c90783bbfa3d7b196ceabe0536b; $> $> # ESP SAs using "
"192 bit long keys (168 + 24 parity)  $> add 192.168.2.31 192.168.2.32 esp "
"0x201 -E 3des-cbc 0x7aeaca3f87d060a12f4a4487d5a5c3355920fae69a96c831; $> add "
"192.168.2.32 192.168.2.31 esp 0x301 -E 3des-cbc "
"0xf6ddb555acfd9d77b03ea3843f2653255afe8eb5573965df; $> $> # Security "
"policies $> spdadd 192.168.2.31 192.168.2.32 any -P in ipsec "
"esp/transport//require ah/transport//require; $> spdadd 192.168.2.32 "
"192.168.2.31 any -P out ipsec esp/transport//require ah/transport//require; "
"$> # End setkey.conf $> EOF"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:119
msgid ""
"Now load your security association and security policy settings into the "
"kernel: $> setkey -f /etc/setkey.conf"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:124
msgid ""
"To create your own secret keys use $> dd if=/dev/random count=16 bs=1| xxd "
"-ps for the md5-hmac key and/or for the 3des keys. Insert your keys in the "
"right position of setkey.conf pairs.  $> dd if=/dev/random count=24 bs=1| "
"xxd -ps"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:126
msgid "They generate a random value with each call that may be used with ipsec."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/ipsec.txt:129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"4. Finish\n"
"You should create some kind of script that loads the contents of setkey.conf "
"into the kernel during each boot. Otherwise the IP traffic will NOT be "
"encrypted/signed after a reboot until a manual load. To check whether your "
"setup works use some tool like tcpdump.\n"
msgstr ""

